THOUGHT: The crash arises from MemorySSA verification after non-trivial simple loop unswitch. In the code, MSSA cloning updates (updateForClonedLoop and updateExitBlocksForClonedLoop) are performed only in the partial-unswitch branch (the else with BI). In the full-unswitch branch, we modify CFG (create new branch, erase terminator, clone blocks), but we don't perform corresponding MSSA updates before deleting dead cloned blocks. This can lead to MemoryDef not dominating its uses, triggering the assertion. The fix is to perform the same MSSAU cloning updates in the full-unswitch path when MSSAU is present, before proceeding with deletions, mirroring the partial path.

```bash
applypatch << 'PATCH'
*** Begin Patch
*** Update File: llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/SimpleLoopUnswitch.cpp
@@
-  if (FullUnswitch) {
+  if (FullUnswitch) {
@@
     // Create a new unconditional branch to the continuing block (as opposed to
     // the one cloned).
     Instruction *NewBI = BranchInst::Create(RetainedSuccBB, ParentBB);
     NewBI->setDebugLoc(NewTI->getDebugLoc());

     // After MSSAU update, remove the cloned terminator instruction NewTI.
     NewTI->eraseFromParent();
+    // Perform MSSA cloning updates for full unswitch as well. We have cloned
+    // parts of the loop CFG and need to inform MSSA before any deletions to
+    // keep definitions dominating their uses.
+    if (MSSAU) {
+      DT.applyUpdates(DTUpdates);
+      DTUpdates.clear();
+      for (auto &VMap : VMaps)
+        MSSAU->updateForClonedLoop(LBRPO, ExitBlocks, *VMap,
+                                   /*IgnoreIncomingWithNoClones=*/true);
+      MSSAU->updateExitBlocksForClonedLoop(ExitBlocks, VMaps, DT);
+    }
